<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="react-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>javascript-developer</domain>
    <summary>Modern React patterns: feature-based structure, typed components, custom hooks, Context, state management routing, and memoization rules for React 18+ with TypeScript strict mode.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>react</tag>
      <tag>hooks</tag>
      <tag>typescript</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>React Patterns</title>
    <summary>Feature-based folder structure, typed functional components, custom hooks, Context provider pattern, state management decision tree, and memoization rules for maintainable React apps.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>React's flexibility makes it easy to write hard-to-maintain code. These patterns enforce consistent colocated state, prevent prop-drilling via Context, and ensure memoization is applied only where measured — avoiding the common trap of over-optimizing.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building a new React feature module (auth, dashboard, checkout)</item>
        <item>Deciding where to put state (server vs. local vs. global)</item>
        <item>Extracting reusable async data-fetching logic into a custom hook</item>
        <item>Wrapping third-party state in a typed Context provider</item>
        <item>Optimizing a component that profiling shows as a bottleneck</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple presentational components with no state — just write JSX</item>
        <item>When TanStack Query is already in use for server state — don't duplicate with useEffect fetching</item>
        <item>When Zustand already handles global UI state — don't add a Context layer on top</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="React Project Structure and Component Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Organize code by feature, not by file type. Each feature owns its components, hooks, API client, and types.</statement>
        <rationale>Feature cohesion reduces cross-directory jumps during changes; file-type grouping (components/, hooks/, types/) creates scattered coupling.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[src/
├── components/        # Shared UI primitives (Button, Input)
│   └── ui/
├── features/
│   ├── auth/
│   │   ├── components/
│   │   ├── hooks/
│   │   ├── api.ts
│   │   └── types.ts
│   └── dashboard/
├── hooks/             # Truly shared custom hooks
├── utils/             # Pure utility functions
├── types/             # Shared TypeScript types
├── lib/               # Third-party wrappers
└── app/               # Next.js app directory / routes]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Functional Component Conventions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use function declarations (not arrow functions) for components; always declare props as a named interface.</statement>
        <rationale>Function declarations are hoisted and show the component name in stack traces; named prop interfaces document the API and enable IDE autocomplete.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[interface UserCardProps {
  user: User;
  onEdit?: (id: string) => void;
  className?: string;
}

export function UserCard({ user, onEdit, className }: UserCardProps): React.ReactElement {
  const handleEdit = () => {
    onEdit?.(user.id);
  };

  return (
    <div className={cn('card', className)}>
      <h3>{user.name}</h3>
      <p>{user.email}</p>
      {onEdit && <button onClick={handleEdit}>Edit</button>}
    </div>
  );
}]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Exporting anonymous arrow function components: export default () => &lt;div /&gt;</description>
        <reason>Anonymous components show as "Unknown" in React DevTools and error stack traces, making debugging harder.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Custom Hooks and Context Pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define an explicit return interface for every custom hook; do not return a plain tuple for hooks with more than two values.</statement>
        <rationale>Named return properties self-document intent at the call site and survive refactoring without breaking destructuring order.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[interface UseUserResult {
  user: User | null;
  isLoading: boolean;
  error: Error | null;
  refetch: () => Promise<void>;
}

export function useUser(userId: string): UseUserResult {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
  const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState<Error | null>(null);

  const refetch = useCallback(async () => {
    setIsLoading(true);
    setError(null);
    try {
      const data = await fetchUser(userId);
      setUser(data);
    } catch (err) {
      setError(err instanceof Error ? err : new Error('Unknown error'));
    } finally {
      setIsLoading(false);
    }
  }, [userId]);

  useEffect(() => {
    void refetch();
  }, [refetch]);

  return { user, isLoading, error, refetch };
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Context Provider Pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Initialize Context with null and throw in the consumer hook if accessed outside the provider.</statement>
        <rationale>createContext(undefined) or a fake default silently provides wrong values; throwing a descriptive error surfaces the bug immediately.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[interface AuthContextValue {
  user: User | null;
  isAuthenticated: boolean;
  login: (credentials: Credentials) => Promise<void>;
  logout: () => void;
}

const AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextValue | null>(null);

export function AuthProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);

  const login = useCallback(async (credentials: Credentials) => {
    const userData = await authService.login(credentials);
    setUser(userData);
  }, []);

  const logout = useCallback(() => {
    authService.logout();
    setUser(null);
  }, []);

  const value = useMemo(
    () => ({ user, isAuthenticated: user !== null, login, logout }),
    [user, login, logout],
  );

  return <AuthContext.Provider value={value}>{children}</AuthContext.Provider>;
}

export function useAuth(): AuthContextValue {
  const context = useContext(AuthContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error('useAuth must be used within AuthProvider');
  }
  return context;
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="State Management Decision Tree and Performance">
      <rule>
        <statement>Route state to the correct layer: server state to TanStack Query, form state to React Hook Form, global UI state to Zustand/Jotai, component-local state to useState/useReducer.</statement>
        <rationale>Each state type has different caching, synchronization, and invalidation needs; mixing them in one store produces accidental coupling and stale data bugs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Server state (API data) → TanStack Query / SWR</item>
        <item>Form state → React Hook Form</item>
        <item>Global UI state (theme, sidebar) → Zustand (simple) / Jotai (atomic)</item>
        <item>Component-local state → useState / useReducer</item>
        <item>Cross-component state in same feature → Context + useReducer</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Memoization Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Memoize only after profiling confirms a re-render problem; default to no memoization for simple computations.</statement>
        <rationale>useMemo and useCallback add overhead (allocation + comparison); blindly applying them for every value creates more work, not less.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[// Memoize expensive sort: items array changes trigger re-sort
const sortedItems = useMemo(
  () => items.slice().sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)),
  [items],
);

// Memoize callbacks passed to memoized children to preserve referential equality
const handleItemClick = useCallback((id: string) => {
  setSelectedId(id);
}, []);]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing inline objects or arrays as JSX props: &lt;Comp style={{ color: 'red' }} /&gt;</description>
        <reason>A new object is created on every render, breaking React.memo equality checks and causing unnecessary child re-renders.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
  </content>
</methodology>
